pomesus transpacificus</em>)\r\n\r\nDetermining parentage and mating strategies in a natural spawning experiment with Delta smelt (<em>Hypomesus transpacificus</em>)\r\n\r\nUsing next-generation sequencing techniques to inform the reintroduction of the threatened Paiute cutthroat trout (<em>Oncorhynchus clarkii seleniris</em>)\r\n\r\nConservation and landscape genetics and sex-determination of White-tailed (<em>Buteo albicaudatus</em>) and Red-shouldered Hawks (<em>Buteo lineatus</em>) in North America\r\n\r\nPhylogenetics and systematics of Indonesian bats using cytochrome-b sequence data\r\n\r\nCurrent and historical phylogeography of tui chubs (Gila bicolor) in the Walker Basin using microsatellites and mitochondrial sequence data'),(1387,402,'__research_projects','field_530507efae298'),(1388,402,'_publications','<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Published</span>\r\n\r\n<strong>Finger, A. J.</strong>, Stephens, M. R., Clipperton, N. C. and May B. P. (2009) Characterization of Six Single Nucleotide Polymorphisms Distinguishing Lahontan and Paiute cutthroat trouts. <em>Molecular Ecology Resources</em> 9:759-763.\r\n\r\n<strong>Finger, A. J.</strong>, Fishes of the Tuolumne River, book chapter <em>in</em> Confluence v1.0 eds. Jeffrey Mount, Sabra Purdy. University of California press, creative commons licensing. (V. 1.0). <a title=\"ConfluenceTuolumneV1.pdf\" href=\"http://watershed.ucdavis.edu/tuolumne/resources/ConfluenceTuolumneV1.pdf\">http://watershed.ucdavis.edu/tuolumne/resources/ConfluenceTuolumneV1.pdf</a>.\r\n\r\n<strong>Finger, A. J.</strong>, Anderson, E. A., Stephens, M. R., and May, B. P. (2010) Application of a method for estimating effective population size and admixture using diagnostic SNPs: Implications for conservation of threatened Paiute cutthroat trout in Silver King Creek, California. <em>Canadian Journal of Fisheries and Aquatic Sciences</em>, 68:1369-1386.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Manuscripts in Progress</span>\r\n\r\n<strong>Finger, A. J.</strong>, Parmenter, S. P. and May, B. P. “Microsatellites reveal genetic drift and population bottlenecks in refuge populations of the Owens pupfish (Cyprinodon radiosus). (submitted with minor revisions to Transactions of the American Fisheries Society)\r\n\r\nStephens, M. R., <strong>Finger, A. J.</strong>, Clipperton, N. C., and May, B.P. “Conservation genetic status of native Little Kern golden trout using SNP and microsatellite markers.”'),(1389,402,'__publications','field_5305081a9bade'),(1390,405,'_edit_last','1'),(1391,405,'_edit_lock','1394645913:1'),(1392,406,'_wp_attached_file','2014/03/andrea_schreier_cv_2012.pdf'),(1393,407,'_wp_attached_file','2014/03/andrea_schreier_profile_image.jpg'),(1394,407,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:300;s:6:\"height\";i:225;s:4:\"file\";s:41:\"2014/03/andrea_schreier_profile_image.jpg\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:1:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:41:\"andrea_schreier_profile_image-150x150.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:150;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:10:{s:8:\"aperture\";d:2.7999999999999998;s:6:\"credit\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"camera\";s:8:\"DMC-FX12\";s:7:\"caption\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";i:1252917782;s:9:\"copyright\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"focal_length\";s:3:\"5.8\";s:3:\"iso\";s:3:\"100\";s:13:\"shutter_speed\";s:9:\"0.0015625\";s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";}}'),(1395,407,'_wp_attachment_image_alt','Andrea Schreier Profile Image'),(1396,405,'_work_position','Postdoctoral Researcher\r\nAlumna of the Graduate Group of Ecology'),(1397,405,'_email','amdrauch@ucdavis.edu'),(1398,405,'_work_address','One Shields Ave, Davis, CA  95616'),(1399,405,'_work_phone','(530) 752-0664'),(1400,405,'_profile_picture','407'),(1401,405,'__profile_picture','field_52fbc541cfb03'),(1402,405,'_curriculum_vitae','406'),(1403,405,'__curriculum_vitae','field_52fbce8765544'),(1404,405,'_alumni','1'),(1405,405,'__alumni','field_5310d6b20e086'),(1406,405,'_people_category','Project Scientists'),(1407,405,'__people_category','field_530b901b0ca70'),(1408,405,'_education','PhD, UC Davis, 2012\r\n\r\nMS, Purdue University, 2006\r\n\r\nBS, Hillsdale College, 2003'),(1409,405,'__education','field_530503a0f8e71'),(1410,405,'_research_interests','I am generally interested in using molecular techniques to understand ecological and evolutionary characteristics of fish and other organisms. I am particularly interested in the conservation, ecology, and evolution of ancient polyploid fishes such as sturgeon and paddlefishes.'),(1411,405,'__research_interests','field_530507cebdd0e'),(1412,405,'_research_projects','<strong>Inference of ploidy level in white sturgeon:</strong> Sturgeon belong to the family Acipenseridae, which is thought to be derived from an ancestor with 60 chromosomes. Extant sturgeons have 120, 250, or 360 chromosomes and there is some controversy over the evolutionary ploidy level for these groups. I followed the inheritance of eight microsatellite loci in 15 known families of white sturgeon to infer ploidy level from the mode of inheritance and gene copy number at each locus.\r\n\r\n<strong>Examination of white sturgeon population structure across the species range:</strong> Due to the highly duplicated nature of the white sturgeon genome, little work had been done to evaluate population structure until recently. With the help of agency biologists across the West Coast, I assembled a collection of tissue samples from white sturgeon inhabiting nearly all reaches of the Sacramento-San Joaquin, Columbia-Snake, and Fraser River drainages. I used microsatellite markers to examine population structure within and among drainages and used these to address critical unknowns in white sturgeon conservation and management.\r\n\r\n<strong>Genetic monitoring of Kootenai River white sturgeon conservation aquaculture program:</strong> I use neutral markers to monitor genetic diversity loss in a conservation aquaculture program for an endangered white sturgeon population suffering from decades of recruitment failure. Genetic data are also used for identification of individual broodstock and parentage analysis.\r\n\r\n<strong>Examining effectiveness of two conservation aquaculture techniques for preserving genetic diversity in Upper Columbia River white sturgeon:</strong> Traditional sturgeon conservation aquaculture involves the capture of wild, sexually mature adults, spawning these adults in a hatchery, and rearing of their offspring until they are eventually released into the natural habitat. An alternative to this model is larval capture, where fisheries biologists capture larvae that have been naturally spawned and bring them to a hatchery for rearing. I am comparing the amount of genetic diversity preserved by each technique in a conservation aquaculture program for the Upper Columbia River white sturgeon.\r\n\r\n<strong>Evaluating incidence of spontaneous autopolyploidy in white sturgeon aquaculture programs:</strong> In my dissertation research I discovered individuals of abnormal ploidy at a commercial white sturgeon caviar farm in California. It is uncertain what aspect of artificial culture is resulting in spontaneous genome duplication. Because culture techniques are similar in commercial and conservation aquaculture, it is possible that this phenomenon is occurring in conservation hatcheries for white sturgeon. In collaboration with Daphne Gille, I am working to determine the incidence of unintentional induction of abnormal ploidy on the commercial caviar farm and in the Kootenai River white sturgeon conservation aquaculture program.\r\n\r\n<strong>Estimating heritability of ovarian adiposity and caviar yield in cultured white sturgeon:</strong> Increasing the efficiency and cost-effectiveness of commercial caviar production furthers sturgeon conservation goals by providing a sustainable alternative to wild-harvested caviar. Current white sturgeon caviar production is hindered by the incidence of ovarian adiposity in farm populations. Individuals with ovarian adiposity, or fatty ovaries, produce low yields of low quality caviar. Daphne Gille and I are collaborating with an interdisciplinary team of scientists to determine the influence of genetic and environmental factors on the ovarian adiposity trait. If found to be heritable, the identification of genetic markers associated with genes controlling this trait will aid in selective breeding to reduce its incidence in farm populations.\r\n\r\n<strong>Genetic management plan for Snake River white sturgeon:</strong> In collaboration with scientists at Idaho Power Corporation, I am using information on the population structure of white sturgeon within the Columbia/Snake River system generated by my dissertation research to write a genetic management plan for the Snake River. The management plan will delineate white sturgeon management units based on genetic differentiation among regions in the River and provide recommendations for broodstock selection for conservation aquaculture.'),(1413,405,'__research_projects','field_530507efae298'),(1414,405,'_publications','<strong>Drauch Schreier, A.</strong>, B. Mahardja, and B. May. Variable patterns of population structure revealed across the range of the ancient octoploid white sturgeon, <em>Acipenser transmontanus. Submitted to Transactions of the American Fisheries Society.</em>\r\n\r\nNelson, T. C., P. Doukakis, S. T. Lindley, <strong>A. Drauch Schreier</strong>, J. E. Hightower, L. R. Hildebrand, R. E. Whitlock, and M. A. H. Webb. Modern technologies for an ancient fish: tools to inform management of migratory sturgeon stocks. <em>Submitted to PLoS ONE.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Drauch Schreier, A.</strong>, B. Mahardja, and B. May. 2012. Hierarchical patterns of population structure in the endangered Fraser River white sturgeon, Acipenser transmontanus, and implications for conservation. <em>In press,</em> Canadian Journal of Fisheries and Aquatic Sciences.\r\n\r\n<strong>Drauch Schreier, A.</strong>, J. Rodzen, S. Ireland, and B. May. 2011. Genetic techniques inform conservation aquaculture of the endangered Kootenai River white sturgeon, <em>Acipenser transmontanus.</em> Endangered Species Research 16:65-75.\r\n\r\n<strong>Drauch Schreier, A.</strong>, D. A. Gille, B. Mahardja, and B. May. 2011. Neutral markers confirm the octoploid origin and reveal spontaneous polyploidy in white sturgeon, <em>Acipenser transmontanus</em>. Journal of Applied Ichthyology 27(Suppl 2): 24-33.\r\n\r\nAnders, P., <strong>A. Drauch Schreier</strong>, J. Rodzen, M. Powell, and S. Narum. 2011. A review of genetic evaluation tools for conservation and management of sturgeons: Roles, benefits, and limitations. Journal of Applied Ichthyology 27(Suppl 2): 3-11.\r\n\r\n<strong>Drauch, A. M.</strong>, B. E. Fisher, E. K. Latch, J. A. Fike, and O. E. Rhodes, Jr. 2008. Evaluation of a remnant lake sturgeon population’s utility as a source for reintroductions in the Ohio River system. Conservation Genetics 9:1195-1209.\r\n\r\nBörk, K. B., <strong>A. M. Drauch</strong>, J. A. Israel, J. K. Pedroia, J. Rodzen, and B. P. May. 2008. Development of new microsatellite DNA primers for green and white sturgeon. Conservation Genetics 9:973-979.\r\n\r\nFike, J. A., <strong>A. M. Drauch</strong>, J. C. Beasley, G. Dharmarajan, and O. E. Rhodes, Jr. 2007. Development of fourteen multiplexed microsatellite loci for raccoons (Procyon lotor). Molecular Ecology Notes 7: 525-527.\r\n\r\n<strong>Drauch, A. M.</strong> and O. E. Rhodes, Jr. 2007. Genetic evaluation of the lake sturgeon reintroduction program in the Mississippi and Missouri Rivers. North American Journal of Fisheries Management 27(2): 434-442.'),(1415,405,'__publications','field_5305081a9bade'),(1416,405,'_thumbnail_id','83'),(1417,408,'_edit_last','1'),(1418,408,'_edit_lock','1395080957:1'),(1419,409,'_wp_attached_file','2014/03/melinda_baerwald_2012_cv.pdf'),(1420,410,'_wp_attached_file','201