82'),(2372,480,'__profile_picture','field_52fbc541cfb03'),(2373,480,'_curriculum_vitae','481'),(2374,480,'__curriculum_vitae','field_52fbce8765544'),(2375,480,'_alumni','0'),(2376,480,'__alumni','field_5310d6b20e086'),(2377,480,'_work_position','M.S. Student\r\nGraduate Group of Ecology'),(2378,480,'__work_position','field_5320970428360'),(2379,480,'_email','bmahardja@ucdavis.edu'),(2380,480,'__email','field_532097d86af9d'),(2381,480,'_work_address',''),(2382,480,'__work_address','field_53209806c81da'),(2383,480,'_work_phone','(530) 752-6351'),(2384,480,'__work_phone','field_5320982dc81db'),(2385,480,'_people_category','Graduate Students'),(2386,480,'__people_category','field_530b901b0ca70'),(2387,480,'_education','2009 – University of California, Davis - B. S. in Genetics &amp; Anthropology\r\n\r\nExpected in 2013 - University of California, Davis - M. S. in Ecology'),(2388,480,'__education','field_530503a0f8e71'),(2389,480,'_research_interests','My main research interest lies in the use of molecular tools to aid conservation management of threatened species. Although the primary focus of my research has been on the population structure and evolutionary history of native freshwater Californian fish species, I believe that the application of molecular techniques transcends taxon boundaries and may answer crucial biological questions for imperiled species in any location.'),(2390,480,'__research_interests','field_530507cebdd0e'),(2391,480,'_research_projects','<strong>Demographic connectivity and viability of two distinct splittail (</strong><em>Pogonichthys macrolepidotus</em><strong>) populations in the San Francisco estuary</strong>\r\n\r\nDue to habitat alteration, overexploitation, and introduction of exotic species, most of the native fish fauna in the San Francisco Estuary are experiencing a population decline. The splittail (<em>Pogonichthys macrolepidotus</em>) is Californian cyprinid fish species which resides in the bay during the summer and migrates upstream to spawn in floodplains and river margins in the winter and spring. This species was once listed as a threatened species under the Endangered Species Act and is still considered as a “Species of Special Concern” by the California Department of Fish and Game. Lower abundance indices in recent years and an ongoing status review present a clear need for a better understanding of the population dynamics and life history of the species.\r\n\r\nMy research is a part of a multifaceted study on the connectivity of different splittail populations funded by the Delta Science Program. In 2007, research conducted by Dr. Melinda Baerwald (currently a project scientist here in the Department of Animal Science) revealed that splittails are comprised of two distinct populations: one from the Sacramento and San Joaquin Rivers, and another from the Petaluma and Napa Rivers. Past studies on the species have focused on the Central Valley population and little is known about the less abundant Petaluma-Napa population. The focus of my study will be to estimate the effective and census population size of each population as well as to assign captured adult splittail to their respective population of origin. We will develop new microsatellite markers for this study in addition to the thirteen original microsatellite loci utilized in the previous research. We hypothesize that the Petaluma-Napa River population will be much lower in abundance due to a more sparse spawning habitat. Population and genetic diversity estimates acquired from this study will further our understanding of the ever-changing San Francisco Estuary ecosystem and provide much needed information for a better management of the species.'),(2392,480,'__research_projects','field_530507efae298'),(2393,480,'_publications','Schreier, A.D., B. Mahardja, and B. May. 2013. Hierarchical patterns of population structure in the endangered Fraser River white sturgeon, <em>Acipenser transmontanus</em>, and implications for conservation. Can. J. Fish. &amp; Aquat. Sci. 69:1968-1980 (<a title=\"2013_Schreier_Fraser_river_white_sturgeon.pdf\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Brian_Mahardja_files/2013%20-%20Schreier%20Fraser%20river%20white%20sturgeon.pdf\">pdf</a>).\r\n\r\nMahardja, B., B. May, and M. Baerwald. 2012. Characterization of 36 additional microsatellite loci in splittail (<em>Pogonichthys macrolepidotus</em>) and cross-amplification in five other native Californian cyprinid species. Cons. Gen. Res. 4(4):917-921 (<a title=\"2012_Mahardja_et_al._Cyprinid_Microsat_note.pdf\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Brian_Mahardja_files/2012%20Mahardja%20et%20al.%20-%20Cyprinid%20Microsat%20note.pdf\">pdf</a>).\r\n\r\nSchreier, A.D., D. Gille, B. Mahardja, and B. May. 2011. Neutral markers confirm the octoploid origin and reveal spontaneous polyploidy in white sturgeon, <em>Acipenser transmontanus</em>. J. Appl. Ichthiol. 27:24-33 (<a title=\"2011_Schreier_et_al._Octoploid_origin_sturgeon.pdf\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Brian_Mahardja_files/2011%20Schreier%20et%20al.%20-%20Octoploid%20origin%20sturgeon.pdf\">pdf</a>).'),(2394,480,'__publications','field_5305081a9bade'),(2395,483,'_edit_last','1'),(2396,483,'_edit_lock','1395083068:1'),(2397,484,'_wp_attached_file','2014/03/Daphne_Gille_cv.pdf'),(2398,485,'_wp_attached_file','2014/03/daphne_gille_profile_image.jpg'),(2399,485,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:241;s:6:\"height\";i:300;s:4:\"file\";s:38:\"2014/03/daphne_gille_profile_image.jpg\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:1:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:38:\"daphne_gille_profile_image-150x150.jpg\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:150;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:10:{s:8:\"aperture\";d:2.7999999999999998;s:6:\"credit\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"camera\";s:12:\"FinePix E550\";s:7:\"caption\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";i:1172935048;s:9:\