=\"3730Maintenance.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/3730Maintenance.html\">3730xl Maintenance</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"ProtKwash.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/ProtKwash.html\">Proteinase K Wash</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong> Acrylamide gels</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Acrylamide.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Acrylamide.html\">Acrylamide Gel </a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"AcGelpour.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/AcGelpour.html\">Pouring</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"AcGelRun.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/AcGelRun.html\">Running</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Fluidigm</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Protocols_files/FLUIDIGM EP1 PROTOCOL.doc\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Protocols_files/FLUIDIGM%20EP1%20PROTOCOL.doc\">Fluidigm EP1 Protocol</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Illumina</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Protocols_files/RAD-SEQ Protocol.doc\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Protocols_files/RAD-SEQ%20Protocol.doc\">RAD-SEQ Protocol</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Other</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Protocols_files/tissuesampleprot.pdf\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Protocols_files/tissuesampleprot.pdf\">Tissue Sampling</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Supplies.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Supplies.html\">Ordering and Receiving Supplies</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Supplies.html\" href=\"http://animalscience.ucdavis.edu/gvl/Conservation_Genetics_Fund/Supplies.html\">PCR Tips and Tricks</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Protocols and Procedures','','inherit','closed','open','','217-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:08:00','2014-03-07 21:08:00','',217,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/217-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(319,1,'2014-03-07 21:11:52','2014-03-07 21:11:52','The following product can be made from common laboratory chemicals.\r\n\r\n<strong>Alcoholic Sodium (Potassium) Hydroxide1 </strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Dissolve 120 g of sodium (or potassium) hydroxide in 120 ml water. Allow to cool.</li>\r\n	<li>Dilute to one liter with 95% ethyl alcohol. This solution acts as a general purpose cleaner.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nREFERENCES 1. Gordon and Ford. 1972. The Chemists\' Companion: A Handbook of Practical Data, Techniques and References, pp 428-429. John Wiley &amp; Sons. Rev. 04/97','Glassware Cleaner','','publish','closed','open','','glassware-cleaner','','','2014-03-07 21:11:52','2014-03-07 21:11:52','',217,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/?page_id=319',0,'page','',0),(320,1,'2014-03-07 21:11:52','2014-03-07 21:11:52','The following product can be made from common laboratory chemicals.\r\n\r\n<strong>Alcoholic Sodium (Potassium) Hydroxide1 </strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Dissolve 120 g of sodium (or potassium) hydroxide in 120 ml water. Allow to cool.</li>\r\n	<li>Dilute to one liter with 95% ethyl alcohol. This solution acts as a general purpose cleaner.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nREFERENCES 1. Gordon and Ford. 1972. The Chemists\' Companion: A Handbook of Practical Data, Techniques and References, pp 428-429. John Wiley &amp; Sons. Rev. 04/97','Glassware Cleaner','','inherit','closed','open','','319-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:11:52','2014-03-07 21:11:52','',319,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/319-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(321,1,'2014-03-07 21:14:00','2014-03-07 21:14:00','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Making dNTP’s (Promega) </span></h3>\r\n<strong>NOTES:</strong>\r\n\r\nStock is kept on top shelf of -80° freezer in the main lab\r\n\r\nStock dNTP concentrations are 100mM each (dATP, dCTP, dGTP, dTTP)\r\n\r\n<strong>DIRECTIONS:</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Pipette 250 ul of each dNTP into a 30ml conical tube</li>\r\n	<li>Add 9000 ul of PCR water (Makes 10 ml total of 10uM dNTP, or 2.5uM each dNTP)</li>\r\n	<li>Mix</li>\r\n	<li>Aliquot 500 ul of mixture into twenty 1.5ml tubes</li>\r\n</ul>','dNTPs (Promega)','','publish','closed','open','','dntps-promega','','','2014-03-07 21:35:27','2014-03-07 21:35:27','',217,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/?page_id=321',0,'page','',0),(322,1,'2014-03-07 21:14:00','2014-03-07 21:14:00','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Making dNTP’s (Promega) </span></h3>\r\n<strong>NOTES:</strong>\r\n\r\nStock is kept on top shelf of -80 freezer in the main lab\r\n\r\nStock dNTP concentrations are 100mM each (dATP, dCTP, dGTP, dTTP)\r\n\r\n<strong>DIRECTIONS:</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Pipette 250 ul of each dNTP into a 30ml conical tube</li>\r\n	<li>Add 9000 ul of PCR water (Makes 10 ml total of 10uM dNTP, or 2.5uM each dNTP)</li>\r\n	<li>Mix</li>\r\n	<li>Aliquot 500 ul of mixture into twenty 1.5ml tubes</li>\r\n</ul>','dNTPs (Promega)','','inherit','closed','open','','321-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:14:00','2014-03-07 21:14:00','',321,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/321-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(323,1,'2014-03-07 21:14:17','2014-03-07 21:14:17','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>For denaturing polyacrylamide gels</strong></span></h3>\r\n<strong>Amounts:</strong>\r\n\r\nFormamide: 200 ml\r\n\r\nBromophenol Blue: 10 mg\r\n\r\nXylene Cyanol FF: 10 mg\r\n\r\nEDTA: 4 ml of 0.5 M pH 8.0 stock\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Transfer into 50 mL conical tubes and store at -20º</li>\r\n	<li>When supply in 4º runs low, thaw one tube and add to 4º beaker</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;','98% Formamide Loading Dye','','inherit','closed','open','','307-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:14:17','2014-03-07 21:14:17','',307,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/307-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(324,1,'2014-03-07 21:14:36','2014-03-07 21:14:36','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">0.05ug/ul for agarose gels</span></h3>\r\n<strong>Amount:</strong>\r\n\r\nLadder stock (1ug/ul): 10ul\r\n\r\nLoading dye (BPB/XC found in fridge): 40ul\r\n\r\nNanopure water: 150ul\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>This makes 200ul - aliquot into two tubes</li>\r\n	<li>Use 1ul in a typical agarose gel</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;','Diluting 1Kb Plus Ladder with Dye','','inherit','closed','open','','309-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:14:36','2014-03-07 21:14:36','',309,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/309-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(325,1,'2014-03-07 21:14:54','2014-03-07 21:14:54','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Dilution of Gel Company Fluorescein Ladder : 50 to 400 bp for Manual Acrylamide Gels</span></h3>\r\nGel Company Ladder Catalog Number: MFK400-MD\r\n\r\nTo make 350 ul total (aliquotted into 10 small tubes):\r\n\r\nIn a tube, add\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>30 ul H2O</li>\r\n	<li>10 ul ladder</li>\r\n	<li>300 ul</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nMix and aliquot into 10 small tubes\r\n\r\nThis dilution is adequate to be visible without agarose-overlay staining when loading 1 ul of diluted ladder to a well. If you are going to use an agarose-overlay, you can dilute this dilution 1:1 with more loading dye.','Gelco Fluorescein Ladder','','inherit','closed','open','','312-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:14:54','2014-03-07 21:14:54','',312,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/312-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(326,1,'2014-03-07 21:17:04','2014-03-07 21:17:04','Dissolve 121.1 g of tris base (sigma # T-1503) in 700 ml of ddH<sub>2</sub>O.\r\n\r\nBring to desired pH (Usually 7.5 or 8.0) with concentrated HCl.\r\n\r\nBring volume to 1L with ddH<sub>2</sub>O.\r\n\r\nFilter with 0.5 micron filter.\r\n\r\nAutoclave.\r\n\r\nStore at room temperature.','1M Tris-Cl','','publish','closed','open','','1m-tris-cl','','','2014-03-07 21:17:17','2014-03-07 21:17:17','',217,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/?page_id=326',0,'page','',0),(327,1,'2014-03-07 21:17:04','2014-03-07 21:17:04','Dissolve 121.1 g of tris base (sigma # T-1503) in 700 ml of ddH<sub>2</sub>O.\r\n\r\nBring to desired pH (Usually 7.5 or 8.0) with concentrated HCl.\r\n\r\nBring volume to 1L with ddH<sub>2</sub>O.\r\n\r\nFilter with 0.5 micron filter.\r\n\r\nAutoclave.\r\n\r\nStore at room temperature.','1M Tris-Cl','','inherit','closed','open','','326-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:17:04','2014-03-07 21:17:04','',326,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/326-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(328,1,'2014-03-07 21:18:43','2014-03-07 21:18:43','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Dilution of Gel Company Fluorescein Ladder : 50 to 400 bp for Manual Acrylamide Gels</span></h3>\nGel Company Ladder Catalog Number: MFK400-MD\n\nTo make 350 ul total (aliquotted into 10 small tubes):\n\nIn a tube, add\n<ul>\n	<li>30 ul H<sub>2</sub>O</li>\n	<li>10 ul ladder</li>\n	<li>300 ul</li>\n</ul>\nMix and aliquot into 10 small tubes\n\nThis dilution is adequate to be visible without agarose-overlay staining when loading 1 ul of diluted ladder to a well. If you are going to use an agarose-overlay, you can dilute this dilution 1:1 with more loading dye.','Gelco Fluorescein Ladder','','inherit','closed','open','','312-autosave-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:18:43','2014-03-07 21:18:43','',312,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/312-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(329,1,'2014-03-07 21:18:46','2014-03-07 21:18:46','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Dilution of Gel Company Fluorescein Ladder : 50 to 400 bp for Manual Acrylamide Gels</span></h3>\r\nGel Company Ladder Catalog Number: MFK400-MD\r\n\r\nTo make 350 ul total (aliquotted into 10 small tubes):\r\n\r\nIn a tube, add\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>30 ul H<sub>2</sub>O</li>\r\n	<li>10 ul ladder</li>\r\n	<li>300 ul</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nMix and aliquot into 10 small tubes\r\n\r\nThis dilution is adequate to be visible without agarose-overlay staining when loading 1 ul of diluted ladder to a well. If you are going to use an agarose-overlay, you can dilute this dilution 1:1 with more loading dye.','Gelco Fluorescein Ladder','','inherit','closed','open','','312-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:18:46','2014-03-07 21:18:46','',312,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/312-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(330,1,'2014-03-07 21:19:41','2014-03-07 21:19:41','<strong>For 100ml of storage buffer:</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>50 ml Glycerol</li>\r\n	<li>1 ml 1M Tris-HCl pH 7.5</li>\r\n	<li>0.29g CaCl<sub>2</sub></li>\r\n	<li>ddH20 to 100ml</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>For 10 ml of Proteinase K stock solution:</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Put 10ml of storage buffer in a 15ml screw-cap tube</li>\r\n	<li>Add 100mg of Proteinase K</li>\r\n	<li>Mix well by inverting until crystals are dissolved</li>\r\n	<li>Put 1ml aliquots into 1.5ml microfuge tubes</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nStore at -20°C','Proteinase K','','inherit','closed','open','','316-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:19:41','2014-03-07 21:19:41','',316,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/316-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(331,1,'2014-03-07 21:21:23','2014-03-07 21:21:23','Add 186.1 g EDTA (disodium, dihydrate, Sigma # E-5134) to 800 ml of ddH<sub>2</sub>0.\r\n\r\nAdd about 20g of NaOH pellets while stirring to bring the pH to 8.0.\r\n\r\nAdd the last few grams slowly to avoid overshooting the pH.\r\n\r\nNote that the EDTA won\'t completely dissolve until the pH is around 8.\r\n\r\nFilter with 0.5 micron filter and autoclave.','.5M EDTA (pH 8.0)','','publish','closed','open','','5m-edta-ph-8-0','','','2014-03-07 21:23:45','2014-03-07 21:23:45','',217,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/?page_id=331',0,'page','',0),(332,1,'2014-03-07 21:21:23','2014-03-07 21:21:23','Add 186.1 g EDTA (disodium, dihydrate, Sigma # E-5134) to 800 ml of ddH<sub>2</sub>0.\r\n\r\nAdd about 20g of NaOH pellets while stirring to bring the pH to 8.0.\r\n\r\nAdd the last few grams slowly to avoid overshooting the pH.\r\n\r\nNote that the EDTA won\'t completely dissolve until the pH is around 8.\r\n\r\nFilter with 0.5 micron filter and autoclave.','.5M EDTA (pH 8.0)','','inherit','closed','open','','331-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:21:23','2014-03-07 21:21:23','',331,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/331-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(333,1,'2014-03-07 21:25:06','2014-03-07 21:25:06','Add 10 mL of 1M Tris-HCl (pH 8.0)* and 2 mL of 0.5M EDTA (pH 8.0)* to 988 ml of ddH<sub>2</sub>0.\r\n\r\nFilter with 0.5 micron filter and autoclave.\r\n\r\n<strong>*1 M Tris-Cl</strong>\r\n\r\nDissolve 121.1 g of tris base (sigma # T-1503) in 700 ml of ddH<sub>2</sub>O. Bring to desired pH (Usually 7.5 or 8.0) with concentrated HCl. Bring volume to 1L with ddH<sub>2</sub>O. Filter with 0.5 micron filter. Autoclave. Store at room temperature.\r\n\r\n<strong>*0.5 M EDTA</strong>\r\n\r\nAdd 186.1 g EDTA (disodium, dihydrate, Sigma # E-5134) to 800 ml of ddH20. Add about 20g of NaOH pellets while stirring to bring the pH to 8.0. Add the last few grams slowly to avoid overshooting the pH. Note that the EDTA won\'t completely dissolve until the pH is around 8. Filter with 0.5 micron filter and autoclave.','1X TE (10mM Tris; 1mM EDTA)','','publish','closed','open','','1x-te-10mm-tris-1mm-edta','','','2014-03-07 21:36:16','2014-03-07 21:36:16','',217,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/?page_id=333',0,'page','',0),(334,1,'2014-03-07 21:25:06','2014-03-07 21:25:06','Add 10 mL of 1M Tris-HCl (pH 8.0)* and 2 mL of 0.5M EDTA (pH 8.0)* to 988 ml of ddH<sub>2</sub>0.\r\n\r\nFilter with 0.5 micron filter and autoclave.\r\n\r\n<strong>*1 M Tris-Cl</strong>\r\n\r\nDissolve 121.1 g of tris base (sigma # T-1503) in 700 ml of ddH2O. Bring to desired pH (Usually 7.5 or 8.0) with concentrated HCl. Bring volume to 1L with ddH2O. Filter with 0.5 micron filter. Autoclave. 