ter (Makes 10 ml total of 10uM dNTP, or 2.5uM each dNTP)</li>\r\n	<li>Mix</li>\r\n	<li>Aliquot 500 ul of mixture into twenty 1.5ml tubes</li>\r\n</ul>','dNTPs (Promega)','','inherit','closed','open','','321-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:35:27','2014-03-07 21:35:27','',321,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/321-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(346,1,'2014-03-07 21:36:16','2014-03-07 21:36:16','Add 10 mL of 1M Tris-HCl (pH 8.0)* and 2 mL of 0.5M EDTA (pH 8.0)* to 988 ml of ddH<sub>2</sub>0.\r\n\r\nFilter with 0.5 micron filter and autoclave.\r\n\r\n<strong>*1 M Tris-Cl</strong>\r\n\r\nDissolve 121.1 g of tris base (sigma # T-1503) in 700 ml of ddH<sub>2</sub>O. Bring to desired pH (Usually 7.5 or 8.0) with concentrated HCl. Bring volume to 1L with ddH<sub>2</sub>O. Filter with 0.5 micron filter. Autoclave. Store at room temperature.\r\n\r\n<strong>*0.5 M EDTA</strong>\r\n\r\nAdd 186.1 g EDTA (disodium, dihydrate, Sigma # E-5134) to 800 ml of ddH20. Add about 20g of NaOH pellets while stirring to bring the pH to 8.0. Add the last few grams slowly to avoid overshooting the pH. Note that the EDTA won\'t completely dissolve until the pH is around 8. Filter with 0.5 micron filter and autoclave.','1X TE (10mM Tris; 1mM EDTA)','','inherit','closed','open','','333-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:36:16','2014-03-07 21:36:16','',333,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/333-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(347,1,'2014-03-07 21:36:41','2014-03-07 21:36:41','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">1X Tris- \"low\" EDTA (TLE) pH 8.0</span></h3>\r\nAdd 10 mL of 1M Tris-HCl (pH 8.0)* and 0.2 mL of 0.5M EDTA (pH 8.0)* to 989.8 (990) ml of ddH<sub>2</sub>0.\r\n\r\nFilter with 0.5 micron filter and autoclave.\r\n\r\n<strong>*1 M Tris-Cl</strong>\r\n\r\nDissolve 121.1 g of tris base (sigma # T-1503) in 700 ml of ddH<sub>2</sub>O. Bring to desired pH (Usually 7.5 or 8.0) with concentrated HCl. Bring volume to 1L with ddH<sub>2</sub>O. Filter with 0.5 micron filter. Autoclave. Store at room temperature.\r\n\r\n<strong>*0.5 M EDTA</strong>\r\n\r\nAdd 186.1 g EDTA (disodium, dihydrate, Sigma # E-5134) to 800 ml of ddH<sub>2</sub>0. Add about 20g of NaOH pellets while stirring to bring the pH to 8.0. Add the last few grams slowly to avoid overshooting the pH. Note that the EDTA won\'t completely dissolve until the pH is around 8. Filter with 0.5 micron filter and autoclave.','1X TLE (10mM Tris; 0.1mM EDTA)','','inherit','closed','open','','335-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:36:41','2014-03-07 21:36:41','',335,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/335-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(348,1,'2014-03-07 21:37:10','2014-03-07 21:37:10','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">10X TNE Buffer (100mM Tris; 2.0M NaCl; 10mM EDTA; pH 7.4)</span></h3>\r\nTo 800ml ddH<sub>2</sub>O add:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Trizma Base: 12.1g T-1503</li>\r\n	<li>disodium EDTA: 3.7g E-5134</li>\r\n	<li>NaCl: 116.8g</li>\r\n	<li>pH 7.4 with Conc. HCl</li>\r\n	<li>Bring to volume of 1L with ddH<sub>2</sub>O.</li>\r\n	<li>Filter and autoclave</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nStore at 4 C','10X TNE','','inherit','closed','open','','337-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:37:10','2014-03-07 21:37:10','',337,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/337-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(349,1,'2014-03-07 21:37:30','2014-03-07 21:37:30','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">0.05ug/ul for agarose gels</span></h3>\r\n<strong>Amount:</strong>\r\n\r\nLadder stock (1ug/ul): 10ul\r\n\r\nLoading dye (BPB/XC found in fridge): 40ul\r\n\r\nNanopure water: 150ul\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>This makes 200ul - aliquot into two tubes</li>\r\n	<li>Use 1ul in a typical agarose gel</li>\r\n</ul>','Diluting 1Kb Plus Ladder with Dye','','inherit','closed','open','','309-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:37:30','2014-03-07 21:37:30','',309,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/309-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(350,1,'2014-03-07 21:38:02','2014-03-07 21:38:02','<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">10X TBE(1.1M Tris; 900mM Borate; 25mM EDTA; pH 8.3)</span></h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">****Note: Boric acid dissolves at a pH around 7. One may alternate between adding Trizma Base &amp; Boric acid. Dissolve the EDTA first.****</span></p>\r\nTo 2.5L H<sub>2</sub>O add:\r\n\r\ndisodium EDTA: 37.5g E-5134\r\nTrizma Base: 432g T-1503\r\nBoric Acid: 220g B-0252\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Dissolve and bring pH to 8.3</li>\r\n	<li>Dilute to 4L</li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"line-height: 1.714285714; font-size: 1rem;\">Filter into 5 \"One-Shot\" bottles of 800ml each and autoclave.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>To make 1X TBE:</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Pour entire one-shot into 8L carboy</li>\r\n	<li>Fill to 8L mark with dH<sub>2</sub>O</li>\r\n</ul>','10X TBE “One-Shots”','','inherit','closed','open','','340-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:38:02','2014-03-07 21:38:02','',340,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/340-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(351,1,'2014-03-07 21:45:16','2014-03-07 21:45:16','<strong>Using FujiFilm for quantifying DNA plate</strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Turn FujiFilm, then the computer on.</li>\r\n	<li>Login with regular AniSci password</li>\r\n	<li>Open Image Reader</li>\r\n	<li>Scan plate using 1Laser 1Image, 473nm</li>\r\n	<li>Open MultiGauge 3.0</li>\r\n	<li>Open the image file</li>\r\n	<li>If needed, go to “Display” and change the color intensity.</li>\r\n	<li>Go to “Measure” at the top of the window\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Click on “Plate” in the left tool bar\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Click on “Setting”</li>\r\n	<li>Change the diameter(d) to 5-6mm (the template circles should be within the wells using this measurement)</li>\r\n	<li>Click on the horizontal or vertical plate button and drag the template to your plate</li>\r\n	<li>Template is red when selected</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Set the well with the lowest standard as background by drawing a circle inside the well using the button under BG.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The circle is purple when set as the background</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Next to “Calibration”\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Change unit to ng</li>\r\n	<li>Click on the cursor button under “Select STD band”</li>\r\n	<li>Click on your standards. A box “Band Attribute” will show up.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Choose “Standard” and input your standard concentration</li>\r\n	<li>Standard wells turn green</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Click on “Calibration” under “Density Calib”\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Select the curve function (ex: linear function)</li>\r\n	<li>Choose LAU-BG under the drop-down menu for “Measured”</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Next to “Analysis”\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Result table should appear</li>\r\n	<li>Change the displayed information using the “Table Option”\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Refer to C-146 in the FujiFilm manual for the full definition.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Change the view between “All”, “Comparison”, and “Table” at the bottom of the window.</li>\r\n	<li>Export as .txt file</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n**Since the standard only goes up to 100ng/µL, high concentration (ex: 1000ng) may be not as accurate.','FujiFilm DNA Quantification','','publish','closed','open','','fujifilm-dna-quantification','','','2014-03-07 21:55:11','2014-03-07 21:55:11','',217,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/?page_id=351',0,'page','',0),(352,1,'2014-03-07 21:45:16','2014-03-07 21:45:16','Using FujiFilm for quantifying DNA plate\r\n<ol>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Turn FujiFilm, then the computer on.</li>\r\n	<li>Login with regular AniSci password</li>\r\n	<li>Open Image Reader</li>\r\n	<li>Scan plate using 1Laser 1Image, 473nm</li>\r\n	<li>Open MultiGauge 3.0</li>\r\n	<li>Open the image file</li>\r\n	<li>If needed, go to “Display” and change the color intensity.</li>\r\n	<li>Go to “Measure” at the top of the window\r\n<ol type=\"a\">\r\n	<li>Click on “Plate” in the left tool bar\r\n<ol type=\"i\">\r\n	<li>Click on “Setting”</li>\r\n	<li>Change the diameter(d) to 5-6mm (the template circles should be within the wells using this measurement)</li>\r\n	<li>Click on the horizontal or vertical plate button and drag the template to your plate</li>\r\n	<li>Template is red when selected</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Set the well with the lowest standard as background by drawing a circle inside the well using the button under BG.\r\n<ol type=\"i\">\r\n	<li>The circle is purple when set as the background</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</ol>\r\n9. Next to “Calibration”\r\n\r\na. Change unit to ng\r\n\r\nb. Click on the cursor button under “Select STD band”\r\n\r\nc. Click on your standards. A box “Band Attribute” will show up.\r\n\r\ni. Choose “Standard” and input your standard concentration\r\n\r\nii. Standard wells turn green\r\n\r\nd. Click on “Calibration” under “Density Calib”\r\n\r\ni. Select the curve function (ex: linear function)\r\n\r\nii. Choose LAU-BG under the drop-down menu for “Measured”\r\n\r\n10. Next to “Analysis”\r\n\r\na. Result table should appear\r\n\r\nb. Change the displayed information using the “Table Option”\r\n\r\ni. Refer to C-146 in the FujiFilm manual for the full definition.\r\n\r\nc. Change the view between “All”, “Comparison”, and “Table” at the bottom of the window.\r\n\r\nd. Export as .txt file\r\n\r\n**Since the standard only goes up to 100ng/µL, high concentration (ex: 1000ng) may be not as accurate.','FujiFilm DNA Quantification','','inherit','closed','open','','351-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:45:16','2014-03-07 21:45:16','',351,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/351-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(353,1,'2014-03-07 21:54:24','2014-03-07 21:54:24','Using FujiFilm for quantifying DNA plate\n<ol>\n	<li>Turn FujiFilm, then the computer on.</li>\n	<li>Login with regular AniSci password</li>\n	<li>Open Image Reader</li>\n	<li>Scan plate using 1Laser 1Image, 473nm</li>\n	<li>Open MultiGauge 3.0</li>\n	<li>Open the image file</li>\n	<li>If needed, go to “Display” and change the color intensity.</li>\n	<li>Go to “Measure” at the top of the window\n<ol>\n	<li>Click on “Plate” in the left tool bar\n<ol>\n	<li>Click on “Setting”</li>\n	<li>Change the diameter(d) to 5-6mm (the template circles should be within the wells using this measurement)</li>\n	<li>Click on the horizontal or vertical plate button and drag the template to your plate</li>\n	<li>Template is red when selected</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n	<li>Set the well with the lowest standard as background by drawing a circle inside the well using the button under BG.\n<ol>\n	<li>The circle is purple when set as the background</li>\n</ol>\n\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Next to “Calibration”\n<ol>\n<li>Change unit to ng</li>\n<li>Click on the cursor button under “Select STD band”</li>\n<li>Click on your standards. A box “Band Attribute” will show up.\n<ol>\n<li>Choose “Standard” and input your standard concentration</li>\n<li>Standard wells turn green</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Click on “Calibration” under “Density Calib”\n<ol>\n<li>Select the curve function (ex: linear function)</li>\n<li>Choose LAU-BG under the drop-down menu for “Measured”</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Next to “Analysis”\n<ol>\n<li>Result table should appear</li>\n<li>Change the displayed information using the “Table Option”\n<ol>\n<li>Refer to C-146 in the FujiFilm manual for the full definition.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Change the view between “All”, “Comparison”, and “Table” at the bottom of the window.</li>\n\nd. Export as .txt file\n</ol>\n\n\n**Since the standard only goes up to 100ng/µL, high concentration (ex: 1000ng) may be not as accurate.','FujiFilm DNA Quantification','','inherit','closed','open','','351-autosave-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:54:24','2014-03-07 21:54:24','',351,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/351-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(354,1,'2014-03-07 21:54:58','2014-03-07 21:54:58','<strong>Using FujiFilm for quantifying DNA plate</strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Turn FujiFilm, then the computer on.</li>\r\n	<li>Login with regular AniSci password</li>\r\n	<li>Open Image Reader</li>\r\n	<li>Scan plate using 1Laser 1Image, 473nm</li>\r\n	<li>Open MultiGauge 3.0</li>\r\n	<li>Open the image file</li>\r\n	<li>If needed, go to “Display” and change the color intensity.</li>\r\n	<li>Go to “Measure” at the top of the window\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Click on “Plate” in the left tool bar\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Click on “Setting”</li>\r\n	<li>Change the diameter(d) to 5-6mm (the template circles should be within the wells using this measurement)</li>\r\n	<li>Click on the horizontal or vertical plate button and drag the template to your plate</li>\r\n	<li>Template is red when selected</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Set the well with the lowest standard as background by drawing a circle inside the well using the button under BG.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>The circle is purple when set as the background</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Next to “Calibration”\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Change unit to ng</li>\r\n	<li>Click on the cursor button under “Select STD band”</li>\r\n	<li>Click on your standards. A box “Band Attribute” will show up.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Choose “Standard” and input your standard concentration</li>\r\n	<li>Standard wells turn green</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Click on “Calibration” under “Density Calib”\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Select the curve function (ex: linear function)</li>\r\n	<li>Choose LAU-BG under the drop-down menu for “Measured”</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Next to “Analysis”\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Result table should appear</li>\r\n	<li>Change the displayed information using the “Table Option”\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Refer to C-146 in the FujiFilm manual for the full definition.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Change the view between “All”, “Comparison”, and “Table” at the bottom of the window.</li>\r\n	<li>Export as .txt file</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n**Since the standard only goes up to 100ng/µL, high concentration (ex: 1000ng) may be not as accurate.','FujiFilm DNA Quantification','','inherit','closed','open','','351-revision-v1','','','2014-03-07 21:54:58','2014-03-07 21:54:58','',351,'http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/351-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(355,1,'2014-03-07 21:55:55','2014-03-07 21:55:55','<strong>Buffers &amp; Stocks</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"98% Formamide Loading Dye\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/98-formamide-loading-dye/\">Formamide Loading Dye</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Diluting 1Kb Plus Ladder with Dye\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/diluting-1kb-plus-ladder-with-dye/\">Diluting 1kb Ladder/Dye</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Gelco Fluorescein Ladder\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/gelco-fluorescein-ladder/\">Gelco Fluorescein Ladder</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Proteinase K\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/proteinase-k/\">Proteinase K</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Glassware Cleaner\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/glassware-cleaner/\">Glassware Cleaner</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"dNTPs (Promega)\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/dntps-promega/\">dNTPs (Promega)</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"1M Tris-Cl\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/1m-tris-cl/\">1M Tris-Cl</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\".5M EDTA (pH 8.0)\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/5m-edta-ph-8-0/\">0.5M EDTA (pH 8.0)</a></li>\r\n	<li><a title=\"1X TE (10mM Tris; 1mM EDTA)\" href=\"http://localhost/~psalessi/Genetics_Lab/resources/protocols-and-procedures/1x-te-10mm-tris-1mm-edta/\">1X TE (10mM T